[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Evaluating JDBC Driver Classes**\n\nI’m thinking about the JDBC driver-related aspects, particularly whether the existing data source is correctly set up with DriverDataSource. I should check if the driver auto-registers and how class loading plays into that. There's a need for a custom test driver that isn’t auto-registered with DriverManager. Also, it seems I need a separate test file for DriverDataSource to ensure proper instantiation and verification. I might need to create a public top-level Scala class for testing. What should I name this test class?\n\n**Structuring Driver Test Files**\n\nI need a dedicated `DriverDataSourceTest.scala` within the `com_typesafe_slick.slick_3` package. I'm considering adding a helper driver, either as a top-level class or nested. Could a one-to-one mapping work between the dynamic-access report and test class files, with helper classes inside the same file? It might be better to nest the helper class within a companion object for accessibility. But I also ponder extending `org.h2.Driver` to implement the necessary methods. Should I go with a straightforward top-level class like `NonRegisteringTestDriver` instead?\n\n**Considering Driver Registration**\n\nI’m thinking about subclassing the driver and what happens if the class is loaded but not registered. In that case, using `getConstructor` and `newInstance` might be necessary to ensure it works correctly. It's crucial to confirm that this setup supports the inherited `acceptsURL` method. Would a test-defined subclass of an external driver be feasible here? After all, `DriverDataSource` supports any driver class, so I should be able to work with that flexibility.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_0de03c58d7744231016a29b98a005c819793ccb83ace5b2728\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"content\":[],\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABqKbmmN-a8eBv5uA5kaMGgqgC4PZn0HRZFViJmK2oyNoQGORVvtfL